#SFTechWeek
description:
Monday, Oct 66:00pmPTGMTHosted byãƒ„áµ”â—¡áµ”â›oâ›+510/175 spots leftIn the pre-AI era, building products was a deterministic motion. Founders knew what they were building, users knew what they were getting, and the tension to PMF was in combining the right data and insights. But what happens when products are no longer deterministic? What changes when the product you build is determined by the user, is ever-evolving, and produces rapidly diffusing data points?

title: Understanding the Investor Case for Human Rights in Tech - Exploring the Connection be - #SFTechWeek
description:
Tuesday, Oct 711:00amPTGMTHosted by:â——+3Join Whistle Stop Capital and others for a high-impact expert panel exploring how governance, privacy, and human rights practices in the tech sector have been linked to company value and investor returns. 

This session brings together investors and human rights experts to discuss the benefits of tech companies managing their societal impacts. This workshop will focus on the important conversation underway between technologists, investors, and human rights-concerned citizens, with a focus on identifying where strong accountability drives value creation and mitigates risk.  

With AI reshaping industries at unprecedented speed, we are in a pivotal moment to understand and build strategies that look at the human rights implications of tech investments. title: The New Why of Work - #SFTechWeek
description:
Christine Heckart, CEO and founder of Xapa, has held executive roles at Brocade, Cisco, and Microsoft. She now leads Xapa, an AI-powered platform that helps teams build essential soft skills like empathy, adaptability, and self-awareness.


AI will change what we do at work, but it may also impact the 'why' of work - purpose, growth, impact, and meaning. This session dives into the 150-year history of the changing â€˜whyâ€™ of work (and marriage, too!), including how the unprecedented uncertainty from AI and macroeconomic stressors is rocking our boats and ushering in a new era of growth through transformational change.  As AI takes over task execution, the real value of human workers lies elsewhere in creating meaning, navigating ambiguity, fostering alignment, and leading through uncertainty. But how do we get through this transformation, and what, specifically, is on the other side?
Weâ€™ll discuss how organizations can navigate the massive disruption of AI adoption and ultimately redefine, reinvent, and reimagine â€œwork.â€

title: Panel Discussion: Building Resilient AI - #SFTechWeek
description:
Building Resilient AI: From Experimentation to Production

As AI moves from hype to practical deployment, startups and builders face a critical challenge: how to scale Large Language Model applications with confidence, reliability, and speed. In this panel, SignalFire and Datadog will bring together AI founders and engineers to discuss the evolving challenges of developing, observing, and improving LLM-based products.

The conversation will focus on how teams can approach experimentation, evaluation, and monitoring, and how building confidence in the LLMs they rely on allows them to accelerate product development and deliver trustworthy outcomes. Panelists will share lessons from scaling real-world AI systems, frameworks for creating resilient applications, and perspectives on how the community can establish best practices together.

You will walk away with actionable insights to move faster, mitigate risk, and strengthen your ability to deliver successful AI products to your customers.

Speakers
 - Atai Barkai - CopilotKit.ai Co-founder and CEO

title: APIs to AI: Infrastructure repurposed - #SFTechWeek
description:
As AI agents move to production, a critical infrastructure gap has emerged: how to securely connect AI systems to existing tools and data. Model Context Protocols (MCPs) are emerging as a standard solution, and companies building production implementations are discovering surprising insights.

This fireside chat brings together Jon Dahl (Co-founder and CEO, Mux) and Michael Grinich (Founder and CEO, WorkOS)â€”two technical founders who have shipped production MCP integrations. Mux discovered that years of focus on video infrastructure had created valuable primitives that were the perfect AI building blocks such as storyboard extraction for content moderation, while WorkOS solved the enterprise authentication challenges essential for secure deployments.

Both saw a broader pattern: established API businesses often have infrastructure that becomes incredibly valuable for AI workflows, even when not originally designed for that purpose. This raises questions about how companies should evaluate existing assets for AI integration.

Expect a candid conversation about technical realities, integration speed, and strategic considerations. Two founders discussing what works, what doesn't, and how the MCP ecosystem is rapidly evolving.

This event is a part of #SFTechWeekâ€”a week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Learn more at www.tech-week.com.

title: Just use Postgres (and DuckDB):  a Postgres + DuckDB Community Night #SFTechWeek
description:
Tuesday, Oct 76:00pm â€“ 9:00pmPTGMTHosted by:)*â—Ÿ*â—”â—Ÿâ—”+5Elephants, ducks, weâ€™re all from the same zoo. Join us for an evening exploring how PostgreSQL and DuckDB work better together!

We'll feature talks on integrating DuckDB with existing PostgreSQL workflows, scaling analytics workloads, combining both tools for data engineering use cases, and more. The evening will include technical talks, networking, and discussions about the future of OLAP and OLTP working in harmony â€“ co-hosted by MotherDuck and Dagster!

Agenda: 

**Just use Postgres (and DuckDB)**

The most effective data stacks are often the simplest. This talk demonstrates how combining Postgres and DuckDB creates an elegant and robust platform, freeing you to focus on solving customer problems instead of wrestling with infrastructure.

presented by Jacob Matson, Developer Advocate @ MotherDuck

**Stop Fighting Your Data Platform: Modern Orchestration for High-Velocity Teams**

The modern data landscape demands a new approach: specialized tools working in harmony rather than monolithic solutions trying to do everything. But how do you actually build a stack that delivers on this promise?This talk explores three fundamental principles transforming how we build data platforms: choosing the right tool for each specific job, developing locally before deploying globally, and maintaining unified observability across your entire ecosystem.Through the lens of PostgreSQL's transactional reliability, DuckDB's analytical speed, and Dagster's orchestration intelligence, you'll see how these principles create platforms that scale from your laptop to production while giving teams the visibility and confidence they need to ship reliably.

presented by Yuhan Luo, Head of Product @ Dagster Labs

title: EuReality: XR & AI-driven Hardware Sharing & Happy Hour - #SFTechWeek
description:
Join XR's leading innovators to dive into how AI-driven hardware is crafting a digital reality surpassing the natural world.

A decentralized and organic event that brings together top global XR founders and builders, tech investors, XR ecosystem veterans, and hardware enthusiasts. Communicate in person, share your insights and lessons on what it truly takes to â€œbuildâ€ - the highs, the lows, and everything in between. 

ðŸ‘€ EuReality Event: We help founders create momentum with bold visions and craftsmanship mindset in the digital reality era.  â€” â€œIf a tree falls in the forest and no one hears it, did it happen?â€

------

Behind the Name:

EuReality is the next frontierâ€”a collective, interdependent digital reality where intelligent machines and synthetic data cooperate seamlessly to create a reality beyond the natural.

The past few decades, defined by the fifth Kondratiev wave, marked the small-information era of electronics and the Internet. The coming sixth wave will ignite the big-information era, powered by autonomous intelligent machinesâ€”hardware in the physical worldâ€”that will transform how humanity lives, works, and imagines the future.

Looking further ahead, guided by First Principles that technology evolves in a â€˜Left-Right-Leftâ€™ cycle, the next wave will bring the intelligent revolution. Robots, drones, aircrafts, and autonomous vehicles will generate vast streams of synthetic data, pushing a profound upgrade of the digital realm and crafting a digital reality that surpasses the natural world.

Now is the critical window to shape this future. We stand at a paradigm crossroads: from â€œhuman value comes from our laborâ€ to â€œhuman value comes from who we are.â€ I believe in this shift, and I have named it EuReality.

Inspired by eusocialityâ€”the highest form of social organization in biology, where individuals thrive through cooperation, specialization, and shared purposeâ€”eureality reimagines this principle for technology. It embodies distributed intelligence: machines and systems acting collectively, like a superorganism.

In the digital realm, eureality is not just an upgrade; it is an ecosystem of intelligent machines, smart hardware, and synthetic data working together to create a reality more connected, adaptive, and transformative than ever before.

title: Brisket, Bots, & Breakthroughs #SFTechWeek
description:
Discover how Mindbeamâ€™s Litespark is setting a new industry barâ€”delivering up to 6x faster LLM pre-training, doubling token and batch throughput, and reducing energy costs by over 50% for both startups and enterprises. In this dynamic panel, Mindbeam founder Nii Osae, Principal Research Scientist Moinul Rahat, PhD, and Datology founder Ari Morcos will discuss how advances in training models and agentic AI make real-world deployment possible at scale.

Join us by the fire(side) chat with BBQ to connect directly with the founders of Mindbeam and Datology, share bold ideas, and accelerate your LLM journey.

What We Will Cover:
- Analyze Mindbeamâ€™s Litespark improvements to training efficiency, including measured speed-ups in LLM pre-training, throughput, and resource utilization across practical ML workflows.
- Examine Datologyâ€™s approach to agentic automation, synthetic data, and architectural implications for scalable, robust multi-modal models and real-world enterprise applications.
- Review concrete deployment patterns for generative models, detailing the trade-offs, reproducible benchmarks, and lessons from actual implementations by technical teams.
- Discuss case studies with a focus on design decisions, failure modes, and optimizations as experienced by organizations deploying Mindbeam and Datology in production settings.
- Engage in a participatory Q&A: attendees are encouraged to raise deep technical issues, probe modeling choices, and share practical challenges with panelists who welcome nuanced discussionâ€”not surface-level hype.

Speakers:
- Nii Osae | 2nd time founder with 10+ years of experience in machine learning, applied neural cognitive architecture, scaling large AI applications.

He published scientific research papers on efficient training of large language models and code-generating LLMs in collaboration with Nvidia, AWS, Huggingface, and ServiceNow. He is also a Forbes 30 Under 30 recipient.

- Moinul Rahat, PhD | Moinul is an expert in Quantum Machine Learning (QML) and Quantum Optimization techniques to address complex challenges in particle physics and beyond. He has a PhD from the University of Florida, and was a Postdoctoral Fellow at University of Southampton and University of Valencia.

He developed a hybrid Quantum Generative Adversarial Network (QGAN) architecture with a quantum generator and classical discriminator utilizing PennyLane and PyTorch. 

- Ari Morcos | Ari is the CEO and co-founder of DatologyAI, where the team is dedicated to helping customers build better AI models through improved data quality and methodology.

Prior to founding DatologyAI, he served as a senior staff research scientist at Meta AI Research (FAIR Team) in Menlo Park, focusing on exploring the mechanisms underlying neural network computation and function, and leveraging these insights to advance intelligent machine learning system design.

Join us by the fire(side) chat with BBQ to connect directly with the founders of Mindbeam and Datology, share bold ideas, and accelerate your LLM journey.

title: Ugly Talk: Women Tech Founders #SFTechWeek
description:
In the heart of the worldâ€™s most ambitious startup scene, women founders are still being told the playing field is â€œbetter than ever.â€ The numbers disagree. In 2025, women-led startups in the U.S. pulled just over 2% of all VC dollars â€” in SF, that means the game is still mostly played without you on the roster.

Investors still pitch men on â€œmarket dominationâ€ and women on â€œrisk mitigation.â€ AI, deep tech, and SaaS get the headlines, but the bar for women to raise in those sectors sits higher â€” and often comes with double the scrutiny.

description:
Positive Intelligence Quotient (PQ) measures â€œmental fitness,â€ which is your ability to respond to challenges with clarity and strength. It is about activating your inner sage through curiosity, empathy, and creativity while quieting your inner saboteurs such as self-doubt, perfectionism, over-control, or avoidance. Tech professionals will explore how Positive Intelligence impacts peak performance, resilience, and relationships at work.

WHY IT MATTERS

With many shifts in the world, the economy, and the workplace, markets adjust, strategies pivot, teams reorganize, and AI accelerates possibilities and the unknown.

ðŸŽ¯ Many leaders are left asking the same question: How do I and my team stay focused and perform on what truly matters?

âœ¨ In high-pressure environments, performance is not just about effort:  it is about energy. Leaders who strengthen their mental fitness not only deliver stronger results but also sustain their own well-being and build higher-performing teams.

Â·Â  team performance by 30%

INTERACTIVE DISCUSSION

In a facilitated conversation, attendees will:
Â·Â Identify their dominant saboteurs and sage patterns

Speakers and facilitators will include:

title: Scaling AI in the Enterprise - #SFTechWeek
description:
Wednesday, Oct 83:00pm â€“ 5:00pmPTGMTHosted byáµ”â–¾áµ”áµ”â–¾áµ”Â´â—¡`:)â—”â—Ÿâ—”>.<:â——+9Sujith Joseph is a Principal Engineer and Chief Architect for Enterprise AI & Search in Cisco. He will be presenting about Cisco's Gen AI journey for drastically improving employee experience.

Overview:

Generative AI is everywhere; turning pilots into production at enterprise scale is the hard part. This talk goes behind the scenes of CIRCUITâ€”Ciscoâ€™s #1-used AI tool and enterprise agent ecosystemâ€”now powering 100K+ employee interactions every business day and serving 4,000+ internal teams via LLM-as-a-Service and RAG-as-a-Service (powered by Pinecone Vector Database).

Weâ€™ll unpack the search & cloud engineering that makes it work: an LLM router and agent orchestration layer (built with LangGraph) that routes tasks to the right expert agent/LLM; an AI Agentic Mesh with an Enterprise Agent/MCP Registry for discovery, governance, and reuse; and a security-first model using OAuth 2.0 Token Exchange (RFC 8693) so agents invoke one another with with secure identity propagation and a complete, auditable chain of custody.

Youâ€™ll see how Deep Research Agents blend web + internal knowledge for actionable research reports; Personal & Cisco Data RAG enable safe BYO data (e.g., OneDrive); Data Analysis Agents accelerate insights; and a PPT Agent turns conversations into decks for faster storytelling. With Cisco AI Pods and Leading LLMs, employees can choose the best model for the job. Weâ€™ll close with outcomes from assistants in Sales (GSX), Cisco events (Cisco Live), support, and engineeringâ€”covering proposal generation, RFP compliance, and bug triageâ€”and share the patterns to replicate this in your org.

Takeaways
	â€¢	Reference architecture for agentic, multi-LLM platforms at enterprise scale
	â€¢	Patterns for reliable, stateful agents using LangGraph
	â€¢	Security model with OAuth 2.0 Token Exchange, agent identities, and audit trails
	â€¢	Operating model: registry, governance, and cross-agent reuse
	â€¢	RAG at Scale with Pinecone Vector Database
	â€¢	Practical playbook to move from POC to production with measurable productivity gains

title: Verifiers - Fireside Chat with Will Brown #SFTechWeek
description:
Wednesday, Oct 85:30pmPTGMTHosted byËœâ—¡Ëœ+390/100 spots leftNo slides, no pitches, just war stories, patterns and anti patterns from the engineers who built RL verifiers.

In RLVR, the policy learns whatever the verifier rewards. If the verifier is leaky, exploitable, or miscalibrated, youâ€™re training on lies. This fireside is a candid, practitioner-level dive with builder who have shipped multiple verifiers across tasks (safety, code, tool use).

Weâ€™ll hit:
- What a good verifier actually is: pairwise vs scalar scoring, sparse rewards, decomposition etc.
- Generalization under shift: preventing policy-chasing, leakage, and â€œreward hacking by spec ambiguity.â€
- Calibration & coverage: thresholds, selective prediction, human-in-the-loop only where it moves expected utility.
- Sparse reward tasks: how to design verifiers when feedback is naturally scarce - detecting rare successes, using proxy signals without collapsing to spec drift, and tricks like trajectory-level verification or hierarchical reward shaping.
- If time permits: RL environments and how verifiers are the key.

Non-consensus takes weâ€™ll debate:
- Verifiers should abstain a lot more (prevent the model from training on the wrong signal)
- Train/Configure verifiers on artifacts (traces/tests), not just text.
- Optimize for uncertainty quality, not mean score. 

Who should come: folks shipping LLMs, agents, RLVR stacks; anyone whoâ€™s been burned by a â€œgoodâ€ reward model.

Leave with a concrete checklist, sample specs, and a playbook to make your verifier the bottleneck on truth.

This event is a part of #SFTechWeekâ€”a week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Learn more at www.tech-week.com.

NextView Partner Stephanie Palmeri will lead a conversation with Caleb Hicks, Founder & CEO of SchoolAI, one of the fastest-growing AI companies in education. Since launching in 2021, SchoolAI has scaled to over 1 million classrooms across all 50 states and over 150 countries, becoming a leader in safe, practical AI implementations for educators and students. 

The conversation will dive deep into Caleb's founder journey - the strategic decisions, pivotal moments, and hard-won lessons that enabled SchoolAI to achieve rapid scale in a notoriously difficult market. Whether youâ€™re scaling your own company or looking to understand how AI is reshaping entire industries, this is your chance to learn from a founder whoâ€™s doing it in real time.

ABOUT SCHOOL AI
SchoolAI believes every student deserves to feel seen, supported, and successfulâ€”and that every educator deserves tools that help them make that happen without burning out. Their Classroom Experience Platform helps schools transform the everyday learning experience with powerful, safe AI tools that adapt to how students learn bestâ€”and show teachers whatâ€™s working, whatâ€™s not, and who needs help right now. The outcome? Educators worldwide can reach every student, every day.

ABOUT NEXTVIEW VENTURES 
â€‹NextView Ventures is a high-conviction, hands-on venture capital firm that helps entrepreneurs build companies of consequence to shape a future of collective prosperity. NextView specializes in leading seed and pre-seed rounds in pre-traction businesses that leverage software and AI to tackle mass-market human problems. Since 2011, NextView has invested in 200+ portfolio companies nationally, including Attentive, ThredUP, WHOOP, Devoted Health, Setpoint, TripleLift, and Bobbie.

Stephanie Palmeri is a Partner at NextView Ventures, a seed-specialist firm with offices in San Francisco, New York, and Boston. Stephanie is a founding member of All Raise, a certified coach through the Hudson Institute of Coaching, and serves on the investment committee of Columbia Business School's Lang Entrepreneurial Initiative Fund.

ABOUT CALEB HICKS
Caleb Hicks is a lifelong educator with 20+ years of experience as a classroom teacher, instructional designer, edtech founder, and now CEO of SchoolAI. From creating a teen entrepreneurship program where students started businesses to make $1000, to leading instructional design at Apple, to cofounding Lambda School with innovative income-share agreements, Caleb has focused on creating personalized learning experiences that drive outcomes. title: National Security, Space Robotics, AI, and the Race for the High Ground #SFTechWeek
description:

title: AI in Service of LifeLanguages - #SFTechWeek
description:
Wednesday, Oct 87:00pmPTGMTHosted byË˜â–¿Ë˜*â—Ÿ*^â—¡^+5This salon invites discussion on LifeLanguage companies and their use of AI as a force for good in healthcare.

LifeLanguage companies specialize in building new AI models to understand the languages of lifeâ€”proteins, RNA, and DNA. These companies differ from traditional biotech in that they investigate these languages not with wet-lab approaches but with GPUs. AlphaFold is a leading example in this nascent space and won the Nobel Prize last year. Since then, many startups have modeled their teams after the AlphaFold team, generating sister models that rearrange protein space to form combinations that would have taken evolution hundreds of millions of years to create. These new rearrangements have special properties for curing human disease, strengthening agriculture, and improving manufacturing.

At Ecotone, our mission is to pioneer the next frontier: a model we call Hawaiian Diamond, capable of reading the human genome-as-a-first-language. The challenge is that AlphaFold was possible because of 3D protein data (PDB), where each protein structure serves as a spatial scaffold. For DNA, which is an encoded information space, no such training data exists. Our breakthrough is a novel method to create this data by shifting from spatial to functional understanding. We interlace, arrange, and layer genomic outputs to build a functional scaffoldâ€”the "Point Cloud Feature"â€”that assigns meaning to sections of DNA. Hawaiian Diamond, trained on these scaffolds, will directly pinpoint the root causes of disease, generating the GPS coordinates needed by DNA-guided medications (e.g., CRISPRs) to cure all 10,000 genetic diseases. This will improve the lives of approximately 800 million people and begin the process of fully annotating the mysterious, unresolved sections of our DNA.

Come and discuss over champagne and [maybe] oysters at a secret cozy space.  Thanks to our sponsors Columbia University Venture Community (CVC SF) and #SFTechWeek.

Format: Fireside chat followed by conversation and good vibes.  Location will be made available the day before the event.

This event is a part of #SFTechWeekâ€”a week of events hosted by VCs and startups to bring together the tech ecosystem. Learn more at www.tech-week.com.

description:

From scaling breakthrough technologies to navigating investment dynamics, this conversation will deliver practical takeaways for both founders and investors seeking impact and growth.

Panelist:
Ayush Jain, Structure Therapeutics, Ayush Jain is a highly accomplished and dynamic leader with vast experience in IT strategy, information governance, and cybersecurity. As a CIO, CISO, and CAIO, he is a proven innovator who has developed solutions that expand technical capabilities, increase infrastructure efficiency, and drive business growth.

With expertise in business operations and development, he has successfully led budgetary planning for projects exceeding $100 million. His technical background includes designing global enterprise solutions and developing security and data management programs to lower the total cost of ownership.

Ayush is a recognized speaker on topics including digital transformation, change management, and the strategic application of AI. His ability to bridge the gap between technical complexity and business needs makes him a compelling and insightful voice in the industry.

At AWS, Yin works with early-stage startups, investors, and strategic partners to accelerate innovation in healthcare and life sciences. Prior to AWS, she held business and technical leadership roles at a venture-backed biotech startup building lab automation and software for drug discovery, successfully partnering with Top 20 global pharma and biotechs. Yin holds a PhD in Molecular Biology and Genomics from Cornell University with 10+ publications in top peer-reviewed journals. She enjoys advising founders and serves as a mentor for StartX, Memorial Sloan Kettering, and Springboard.


Nima Ronaghi, PhD Bio: Nima is a Principal at Breakout Ventures, where he uses his deep domain knowledge to identify, support, and build companies pushing the traditional boundaries of product development. Nima earned his doctorate in organic chemistry at Georgia Tech. Funded by the Renewable Bioproducts Institute, his research combined organic chemistry, materials chemistry, and chemical engineering to shed light on the catalytic processes underlying the green chemistry conversion of bio-based feedstocks into industrial products. Nima joined Breakout Ventures in 2021 to provide the firm with subject matter expertise in biomass conversion, materials production, and sustainability. He has helped drive investments across the areas of therapeutics, synthetic biology, industrials, and biomanufacturing, serving as a board director or observer on Copernic Catalysts, ZymoChem, EnPlusOne, and A-Alpha Bio. This evening is for a curated group of leaders tasked with driving operational excellence in an age of disruption.

In today's complex enterprises, a significant disconnect often exists between corporate leadership focused on strategy and the on-ground teams handling real-time execution. This gap leads to misaligned software, failed AI adoption, and missed opportunities. As one strategist noted, the most critical missing asset is an "integrated view from the factory floor to the foxhole". Legacy systems and siloed data are no longer a stable foundationâ€”they are the quickest path to being outmaneuvered.

This roundtable is a candid, off-the-record discussion on closing these operational gaps. We will explore how bespoke AI transformationâ€”powered by embedded engineering talentâ€”can bridge the divide between strategy and execution, modernizing legacy systems and unlocking efficiency gains. We believe, as Napoleon demonstrated, that the greatest results come when leaders are "in the trenches" with their teams, solving real problems on the ground.

Our discussion will center on tangible strategies for:
â€¢ Bridging the gap between executive vision and front-line execution.

â€¢ Deploying agile engineering teams that embed with your staff to drive adoption and deliver practical, iterative solutions, mirroring the successful Forward Deployed Engineer (FDE) model.

title: The Foreign Founder's Stack - #SFTechWeek
description:
Build your US startup the smart way: AI-powered tools, cross-border strategies, and real founder stories.

The future of entrepreneurship is global, and increasingly powered by AI. Foreign founders are building some of the most innovative companies in the US, but navigating incorporation, banking, and immigration can make or break your momentum before you even start.

What you'll learn:

- The operational edge that separates startups that scale from those that stall

- Immigration processing, banking approvals, and compliance workflows

- Strategic cap table structuring when you're building across borders

- Leveraging third-party platforms to streamline operations and keep your team focused on its core edge

Panelists
Andrea Baronchelli Co-Founder & CEO of Aspire, a Y Combinator-backed all-in-one finance operating system serving thousands of businesses across Southeast Asia. Previously part of Lazada's founding team as EVP and CMO, Andrea spent five years scaling the region's leading e-commerce platform before its acquisition by Alibaba. He brings battle-tested experience building category-defining companies across borders.

Logan Jackonis Head of Ops and Services at Commenda, a global entity formation and compliance platform helping startups navigate cross-border incorporation. Logan brings hands-on experience solving the complex international compliance challenges that foreign founders face when entering the US market.

Minn Kim Founder & CEO of Lighthouse, the fastest immigration solution for the world's top technical talent. Previously Partner at On Deck and Principal at Bloomberg Beta, Minn brings deep expertise in immigration, venture, and scaling startups. Based in San Francisco, she's also an avid triathlete and dinner party host.

Moderated by Khanh Dang

Join us for insights from founders who've built the infrastructure layer for cross-border entrepreneurship, and discover how AI is making it easier than ever to build globally.

title: Ugly Talk: Design Founder Takeover #SFTechWeek
description:
Join us for an unfiltered panel discussion exploring what happens when designers take the lead and donâ€™t wait for permission to build. Design Founder Takeover brings together a bold lineup of founders who started their careers in design and are now leveraging AI to build companies from the ground up.

This conversation will dive deep into the unique vantage point of design-led founders: how their design intuition shapes product thinking, what it means to prototype with AI as your cofounder, and how they navigate building, scaling, and fundraising as non-technical founders in a tech-dominated space.

Whether you're a designer dreaming of starting something or just curious about what it looks like when creativity meets code, this is the panel you donâ€™t want to miss.

Who Should Attend: Designers, founders, builders, product thinkers, AI experimenters, and anyone curious about the evolving role of design in startup creation.

ðŸŽ¤ Whoâ€™s on the Panel

Izac Ross - Founder & CEO of Haven Headache & Migraine Center

Izac Ross is the founder and CEO of Haven Headache & Migraine Center, a virtual-first clinic reimagining how millions access expert headache care. Living with migraine since childhood, he brings a rare blend of patient perspective and healthcare innovation experience from Hinge Health, Alto Pharmacy, and Collective Health. At Haven, Izac is building AI-enabled tools and care models that help patients track progress, reduce disability, and find relief. A former product designer, he is endlessly curious about what people need to thrive. Outside of work, Izac enjoys hiking with his dog Parker, ceramics, live music, and biking.


Kris Woyzbun - Co-Founder & CEO of Gumption

Kris Woyzbun is a 2X tech founder and product design executive based in Palo Alto, California. Having held leadership roles at Google, SSENSE, EDITR, and IDEO, and with recognition from IDSA Awards and NVIDIA, Kris's work focuses on building companies and products in consumer technology. Currently building Gumption, an AI Home Design Companion.


Fifi Kara - Co-Founder & CEO of Aster

Fifi Kara is originally from London, now in San Francisco, Fifi has 10 years building consumer and B2B products across the UK, Europe, and US. Most recently at Meta, she led Design for Health & Fitness (AR/VR), was a Staff Designer for Messenger (150M MAUs), and pioneered Workrooms Web. As a two-time founder and early startup hire, she has focused on 0-1 building and scaling. She co-founded a YC-backed fintech in 2019 and joined Bulb as an early design hire, growing usage from 100K to 1.4M MAUs. Fifi is a LSE graduate, Fulbright Scholar and is self-taught in product design and front-end engineering.

She is a NYC Parsons School of Design Dean's List graduate, NCAA Division 1 Ivy League Champion (with Brown University Women's Soccer team), road runner, scuba diver, dancer and acclaimed solar punk artist. In 2020, Fennel created D5WR when schools closed during COVID for 2 years. "In the dark shadow of death*", Fennel and her (then 7 YO) son began going to the beach park together seeking life, energy, and observation-based learning flow state, as school. D5WR campaigned tirelessly to unlock the path for all, forever, to create health for future generations, and particularly for Black & broke folks living in the city. Health = Wealth.

title: Existential AI Risks, Superintelligence and the Future of the Human Brain - Nick Bostrom #SFTechWeek
description:

His work on existential risk, the simulation hypothesis, and AI governance has shaped how the world's leading institutions think about transformative technology.

ðŸ† Jonas von Essen â€” 2X World Memory Champion, co-founder of memoryOS, and holder of multiple world records, including memorizing 100,000 digits of Pi. From game show champion (Jeopardy!, Who Wants to Be a Millionaire) to neurotechnology entrepreneur, Jonas represents the practical frontier of human cognitive enhancement.

What We'll Explore: ðŸ”

â° What are the true existential risks of ASI?

title: Museum of Wearables Evolution at World ID â€“ #SFTechWeek
description:
From calculator watches to Google Glass, humanity has spent decades trying to merge technology with the body. Some designs became icons. Most ended up in drawers.

Museum of Wearables Evolution is a one-night immersive installation at the buzzy new World Flagship Store, iconically located on Union Square. We are thrilled to be partnering with World ID, founded by Sam Altman. Our pop-up exhibit will be sharing their space with the World Orb, the innovative and NVIDIA-powered biometric screening device that distinguishes humans from AI.

This exclusive Taya and Oasis Collective event traces the history of wearable tech: from retro gadgets and failed futures to jewelry that has carried hidden meaning for centuries. Each artifact will be displayed with museum-style plaques, charting what promised to be the future and why it didnâ€™t last.

The exhibition has sneak peeks of Taya - an AI-powered pendant designed as jewelry first, technology second. Itâ€™s our answer to the question: what if wearable tech finally passed the â€œdead battery testâ€?

Sign up for the waitlist here: tayanecklace.com

This event is for founders, investors, designers, and the Tech Week community who care about the intersection of hardware, AI, and culture. Join us to explore the lineage of wearables and see some sneak peeks.
